1. .ICS file auto-writes a calendar entry without user interaction
No click needed. The invite lands directly in the calendar with a malicious URL hidden behind a legitimate-looking join button.
2. Calendar entry survives email deletion
Once processed, the calendar item lives independently. Deleting the email does not remove the lure.
3. Silent URL swap via updated .ICS
Attacker resends the same event UID with a new URL. Calendar entry updates silently — no new email, no alert, victim sees nothing changed.
4. Cancellation cleans the traces
Attacker sends a cancel .ICS after objective is met. Removes the calendar entry, leaves minimal forensic trail.
5. Join button hides the real URL
Calendar clients render it as a styled button. Raw URL is invisible unless user explicitly inspects the link.
6. Proofpoint and Microsoft acknowledged the gap
Neither email filtering nor calendar auditing reliably catches this chain. The attack lives in the space between email security and calendar processing.
